title: For Sale:  PS-90 by FNH with Ammo, Optic, and More
postcontent:
For sale is one FNH Gen 3 PS-90 bullpup style rifle in 5.7x28mm.  You can find more info on the differences online but in essence the newest ones no longer have the auto-sear while this and earlier models do.  When I purchased it, I was told that it was more desirable and sought after due to this fact and so this is why I added this one to my collection.  I've also heard that the construction of the Gen 1-3 may have been superior as they wanted to attract a broader audience with the new Gen 4.  I'm not sure how much of a factor this is as two friends of mine with the Gen 4 have had no complaints.  I'd say it is difficult to go wrong with a PS-90 regardless of the Generation.  

Included with the purchase is a 1-4x optic, which allows the user to rapidly switch from 1x to 4x magnification at the flip of a switch, a Sightmark laser sight, four 50-round magazines, and 250 rounds of ammo.  With the cost of these rounds, the ammo represents a value of nearly $200.  Whether bought locally or online after you factor in shipping and/or tax you'll find this to be true.  The magazines represent a value of nearly $100. Though I paid $30, I now see them online at a price of $25 with promotions sometimes pricing them at $20 but again, keep in mind that shipping and/or tax will augment these figures.  I'm just throwing in the optic and laser as I don't have a need for them anymore but the scope had cost me $300 with the laser costing another $100 or so.  Ignoring the optic, the value of the ammo and magazines puts the cost of this practically new rifle well below the $1,600 I had paid for it just months ago.

I'm selling the rifle at the wife's request due to a new baby on the way, so unfortunately I can only keep what will fit in the safe and I'm keeping primarily just those firearms in 5.56 or 9mm. I hate to let go of this having been able to use it just three times. Putting two mags downrange each time, I estimate only 300 rounds fired down range. The lack of use coupled with the ammo, as I have no other guns in 5.7, are the reasons I'm letting this one go. Yet the ammo coupled with the great design are the main reasons this rifle is so appealing.  The lack of recoil (almost on par with a .22), compact bullpup design, and lightweight, of both the rifle and ammo, make this rifle great for home defense (easily maneuverable in tight spaces with less reloading) and many other applications.  4 mags on their person plus one on the rifle with ease.  I've not seen another rifle for which this could be said. 
 I certainly plan to get another at some point in the future when circumstances allow for it.

With the cost of these rounds, the ammo represents a value of nearly $200.  Whether bought locally or online after you factor in shipping and/or tax you'll find this to be true.  The magazines represent a value of nearly $100. Though I paid $30, I now see them online at a price of $25 with promotions sometimes pricing them at $20 but again, keep in mind that shipping and/or tax will augment these figures.  I'm just throwing in the optic as I don't have a need for it anymore but the scope had cost me $300.  Ignoring the optic, the value of the ammo and magazines puts the cost of this practically new rifle well below the $1,600 I had paid for it just months ago.   

My apologies for the lengthy description above, but as I've received many questions, I hope this will now address these items upfront.  Thanks for looking and please reach out if you have questions I haven't addressed.

Manufacturer: Windham Weaponry Firearm Type: Rifle Flag |  Edit | Favorite 
This is one of the Swedish sniper rifles used during WW11. It is referred to as a model 41-B Mauser in 6.5x55. It sports a Pre War German made Ajack sniper scope dated 1942 and matching numbers 208526 on the mounts These were sold out years ago by Sarco and are import marked under the barrel in front of stock. It is in near new condition in and out with a $1000 Ajack scope, 4x90 Mint bore and action. 1907 dated receiver stamped CARL GUSTAFS STADS GEVARSFAKTORI which is the correct factory for the 41B sniper rifle. Rear sight is marked M/55. 080 on floor plate. 511 on butt plate. 505 on bolt.374 on front band and 208 on rear band, all correct in these rifles pre date WW1 and were rebuilt into snipers in time for the second World war in 1942 where the new rear sight was installed and the 1942 dated scope and new mounts Original sling. Gun appears to be in almost new never issued condition. These are all oriiginal factory bulit sniper rifles. Most of you can probably remember when they were selling these. I bought a couple and socked them away, never shot them but they ae beauties and they are the real deal sniper rifles, this one was not put togehter. C&R
